Semiarid Climate (part 2)¶

In this notebook, we will continue our work about semiarid climate. In the first part, using weather data from INMET, we created a database with indicators about climatological region conditions. Now, we are going to do two tasks:

  • First, import this database.
  • Second, we will import shapefile data (geographic information) of the SUDENE region.
  • Third, we will use an interpolation technique to fill all cities with climate indicators information.
  • Finally, we will plot maps to show the areas with more semiarid conditions.

When solving these tasks, we believe it to be possible to learn more about the geopandas package and an interpolation technique.

Interpolation of weather data¶

As you can see in the previous map, there are no weather stations in all cities of the SUDENE region. Therefore, we should use the interpolation data to fill whole cities with these pieces of information. There are a lot of technics that we could use to do that; the one that we chose was the mean weighted of the five closest pieces of information. The weight is the squared distance from the municipality to the station. Watch:

$$\hat {\text{I}} = \frac{{\text{I}}_{1}{\frac{1}{\text{distance}_{1}^{2}}} + {\text{I}}_{2}{\frac{1}{\text{distance}_{2}^{2}}} + {\text{I}}_{3}{\frac{1}{\text{distance}_{3}^{2}}} + {\text{I}}_{4}{\frac{1}{\text{distance}_{4}^{2}}} + {\text{I}}_{5}{\frac{1}{\text{distance}_{5}^{2}}}}{\frac{1}{\text{distance}_{1}^{2}} + \frac{1}{\text{distance}_{2}^{2}} + \frac{1}{\text{distance}_{3}^{2}} + \frac{1}{\text{distance}_{4}^{2}} + \frac{1}{\text{distance}_{5}^{2}}}$$

To interpolate the data, we will use a loop to pass to whole cities inside our DF. Inside the loop, we will need to create a data frame intermediary to facilitate our calculations. We will show the intermediary DF logic below:

Note: In the code below, we are exemplifying the city in the zero position index. However, in the loop, we will change it to go through whole towns.

In [17]:
##We will concatenate a DF informing the distances with one informing the values of the indicators.
pd.concat([pd.DataFrame(geodf_indicators.geometry.distance(sudene_geo_info.centroid[0]).sort_values()[0:5],
                        columns = ['DISTANCIA']), #DF informing the distances
           geodf_indicators. #DF informing the values of the indicators
           loc[geodf_indicators. #Here notice that we are locating the five closest stations.
               geometry.
               distance(sudene_geo_info.
                        centroid[0]).
               sort_values()[0:5].
               index][["MEDIA_PREC_ANUAL",
                       "Aridity Index",
                       "dias_s_chuv"]]],axis=1)

Now let's go through the loop

  • First, we created the intermediate DF.
  • Second, in this DF, we will add a column with the value of the weights used in our average.
  • Third, we will calculate the average powered by the weights for each indicator.
  • Finally, we will empty the intermediate DF before restarting the loop process again.
  • It is worth mentioning that this code takes a little while to be executed entirely, as there are many cities in our database. So we added a time marker at the beginning of the code and another at the end so you can see how long it will take on your computer (in mine, it takes an average of 10 minutes).
In [18]:
print(datetime.datetime.now().time()) #Time marker

for i in list(range(0,len(sudene_geo_info))): ##For each city/index
    
    ##Creating an intermediate DF
    df_inter = pd.concat([pd.DataFrame(geodf_indicators.
                                       geometry.
                                       distance(sudene_geo_info.centroid[i]).
                                       sort_values()[0:5],
                                       columns = ['DISTANCIA']),
                          geodf_indicators.
                          loc[geodf_indicators.
                              geometry.
                              distance(sudene_geo_info.
                                       centroid[i]).
                              sort_values()[0:5].
                              index][["MEDIA_PREC_ANUAL",
                                      "Aridity Index",
                                      "dias_s_chuv"]]],axis=1)
    
    ##Creating the weights for the interpolation
    df_inter['PESOS'] = (1/(df_inter['DISTANCIA']**2))
    
    ##Average annual precipitation
    sudene_geo_info.loc[i,"MEDIA_PREC_ANUAL"] = ((df_inter["MEDIA_PREC_ANUAL"]*
                                                  df_inter["PESOS"]).sum())/df_inter["PESOS"].sum()
    
    ##Aridity Index
    sudene_geo_info.loc[i,"Aridity Index"] = ((df_inter["Aridity Index"]*
                                               df_inter["PESOS"]).sum())/df_inter["PESOS"].sum()
    
    ##Days without rain
    sudene_geo_info.loc[i,"dias_s_chuv"] = ((df_inter["dias_s_chuv"]*
                                             df_inter["PESOS"]).sum())/df_inter["PESOS"].sum()
    
    ##Cleaning the intermediate DF
    df_inter = None
    
print(datetime.datetime.now().time()) #Time marker

Maps¶

Now we will use the information from our data frame "sudene_geo_info" to build colormaps that allow us to analyze the semiarid condition of cities.

In [21]:
##Average annual precipitation
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 10)) #Building the figure

#Colormaps
sudene_geo_info.plot(ax=ax,
                     column = "MEDIA_PREC_ANUAL",
                     cmap = plt.cm.get_cmap("OrRd").reversed(), #The redder the more semiarid
                     scheme='quantiles',
                     k=5,
                     legend=True)

#Highlighting at the borders of cities
sudene_geo_info.boundary.plot(ax=ax,color = "lightgray", linewidth=0.2)

#Title
plt.title("Average annual precipitation")
